  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Humanitarian Support for Flood Affected Families in Nepal</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Response will address the specific needs of the families as most of the response carried forward currently is focused on a blanket approach in areas where affected populations are concentrated. From our previous experience and assessment carried in earlier emergencies it has been witnessed that during response specific needs are sparsely covered and are most of the times not based on reliable information on the status of families.For that, we will cater to specific needs of vulnerable population such as pregnant and lactating women through nutritional support; people with disability by providing mobility aids; people needing further treatment will be provided with transportation cost for accessing health services; providing school kits to children and further we will provide necessary medication to people with chronic diseases.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The current floods in the Terai region, especially in Bardiya and Dang districts, require immediate assistance as people have been badly affected, losing shelter and needing WASH and livelihoods resources and infrastructure. HI and CA have designed an emergency response that caters to the immediate needs of the people of the affected. We are proposing to provide direct humanitarian assistance to 2000 households (10,000 beneficiaries) in the form of emergency shelter support NFI, hygiene kits and targeted support to the disabled and elderly. The response will also undertake hygiene promotion campaigns targeting 20,000 people. In Bardiya, Christian Aid will be responding in Thakurbaba and Barbardiya municipality and Handicap international will be responding in Dangisharan and Lamahi municipality in Dang district and Rapti Sonari and Narenapur Rural Municipality of Banke district. The CA and HI team has coordinated with other humanitarian agencies as well as local government authorities and the local partners have been part of the Initial Rapid Assessment (IRA) in the proposed districts to ensure there are no geographical or intervention overlaps in the target locations.</narrative>
  </description>
